>>> 04 ex3 in-place sed
=== original input.txt ===
hello world
foo bar
hello again

=== the WRONG way:  sed '...' input.txt > input.txt ===
The shell opens (and truncates) input.txt for '>' BEFORE sed starts
reading it. sed then reads an already-empty file. Result: data lost.
--- bad.txt after the redirect trick (empty!) ---
[bad.txt is 0 bytes]

Is this particular to sed?  No — it is the SHELL doing the truncation,
so the same footgun applies to awk, grep, tr, cat ... any 'cmd f > f'.

=== the RIGHT way #1:  sed -i (in-place, from man sed) ===
HELLO world
foo bar
HELLO again

=== the RIGHT way #2:  write to a temp file then move ===
HELLO world
foo bar
HELLO again

Both correct methods preserve all three lines and apply the substitution.
    [PASS] 04 ex3 in-place sed

